{"time": "2016-09-20T20:51:25.536088", "block": {"name": "text", "subtitles": {}, "source": null, "subtitle_files": [], "feedback_wrong": "", "video": null, "animation": null, "feedback_correct": "", "tests_archive": null, "text": "<p>If we think of decimal numbers in terms of their binary representations (i.e., as a sequence of bits), we can perform various bitwise operations on them. Before talking about bitwise operations, though, let's first (re-)familiarize ourselves with how to think of numbers in binary.</p><p>Recall from elementary school that, in the decimal system, numbers are organized into columns: the <span class=\"wysiwyg-color-black\">rightmost</span> column is the <span class=\"wysiwyg-color-green\"><b>\"ones\"</b></span> column, then to the left of it is the <span class=\"wysiwyg-color-blue\"><b>\"tens\"</b></span> column, then the <span class=\"wysiwyg-color-purple\"><b>\"hundreds\"</b></span> column, etc. We then learned that <b>\"decimal\"</b> meant <b>\"base 10\"</b> and that the rightmost column of a decimal number actually represents <b><span class=\"wysiwyg-color-green\">10\u2070</span></b>, the column to the left of it represents <span class=\"wysiwyg-color-blue\"><b>10\u00b9</b></span>, then <b><span class=\"wysiwyg-color-purple\">10\u00b2</span></b>, etc. For example, the number <b><span class=\"wysiwyg-color-purple\">7</span><span class=\"wysiwyg-color-blue\">2</span><span class=\"wysiwyg-color-green\">9</span></b> can be thought of as <b><span class=\"wysiwyg-color-purple\">(10\u00b2\u00a0\u00d7 7)</span> + <span class=\"wysiwyg-color-blue\">(10\u00b9\n\n\u00d7 2)</span> +\u00a0<span class=\"wysiwyg-color-green\">(10\u2070\n\n\u00d7 9)</span></b>.</p><p><b>Binary</b> numbers work in the same way, but instead of being \"base 10\" (which is the case for \"decimal\"), they are <b>\"base 2\"</b>. Thus, the rightmost column represents\u00a0<b><span class=\"wysiwyg-color-green\">2\u2070</span></b>, the column to the left of it represents <b><span class=\"wysiwyg-color-blue\">2\u00b9</span></b>, then <b><span class=\"wysiwyg-color-purple\">2\u00b2</span></b>, etc. For example, the number <b><span class=\"wysiwyg-color-purple\">1</span><span class=\"wysiwyg-color-blue\">0</span><span class=\"wysiwyg-color-green\">1</span></b> can be thought of as\u00a0\n\n<b><span class=\"wysiwyg-color-purple\">(2\u00b2 \u00d7 1)</span> + <span class=\"wysiwyg-color-blue\">(2\u00b9\n\n\u00d7 0)</span> + <span class=\"wysiwyg-color-green\">(2\u2070\n\n\u00d7 1)</span></b>. In other words,\u00a0<b>101</b> in binary is equal to\u00a0<b>5</b>\ufeff in decimal.</p>", "options": {}}, "id": "111802"}